  "body": "Hi,\r\n\r\nFirst of all, I want to say this is a great library for model interpretability. It can help add more insights into the black-box model, especially for business. Thanks for all the work.\r\n\r\nThe issue I'd like to raise here is about the dependence_plot().\r\n\r\nIf I want to plot the interaction values with dependence_plot:\r\n```\r\nshap.dependence_plot(\r\n    (\"Age\", \"Age\"),\r\n    shap_interaction_values, X.iloc[:2000,:],\r\n    display_features=X_display.iloc[:2000,:],\r\n    xmin = 0,\r\n    xmax = 40\r\n)\r\n```\r\n\r\n**xmin** and **xmax** won't work here. I think it is because **xmin** and **xmax** are not passed into the recursive function here. (https://github.com/slundberg/shap/blob/aff7ee81f33899f0d22972f1e8afff98f0ee7ef3/shap/plots/dependence.py#L91-L112)\r\n\r\nThere is a workaround:\r\n```\r\nshap.dependence_plot(   \r\n    (\"Age\", \"Age\"),\r\n    shap_interaction_values, X.iloc[:2000,:],\r\n    display_features=X_display.iloc[:2000,:],\r\n    show=False\r\n)  \r\nplt.xlim(xmin=0,xmax=40)\r\nplt.show()\r\n```\r\n",
